This lesson uses the same concept as the last lesson with the 'Clockwise Notation'
however we will be applying it to the 'margin' of an element

Remember that clockwise means:
margin-top, margin-right, margin-bottom, and margin-left

The initial code:
<style>
  .injected-text {
    margin-bottom: -25px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .box {
    border-style: solid;
    border-color: black;
    border-width: 5px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .yellow-box {
    background-color: yellow;
    padding: 20px 40px 20px 40px;
  }

  .red-box {
    background-color: crimson;
    color: #fff;
    margin: 20px 40px 20px 40px;
  }

  .blue-box {
    background-color: blue;
    color: #fff;
  }
</style>
<h5 class="injected-text">margin</h5>

<div class="box yellow-box">
  <h5 class="box red-box">padding</h5>
  <h5 class="box blue-box">padding</h5>
</div>

The task required me to give the 'blue-box' class a margin of 40px(pixels) on its top and left side
while only 20px to the bottom and right side

This was my code:
.yellow-box {
    background-color: yellow;
    padding: 20px 40px 20px 40px;
  }

  .red-box {
    background-color: crimson;
    color: #fff;
    margin: 20px 40px 20px 40px;
  }

  .blue-box {
    background-color: blue;
    color: #fff;
    margin: 40px 20px 20px 40px;
  }
  
After making the change in code, it should reflect in your test environment.
As you move on, you'll carry on learning new CSS properties which continue to allow for granular changes.
